Coursework - Data Science II

Justin Gusho, 222222837

For my coursework, I have chosen to undertake a classification problem using the Titanic dataset. The primary goal is to predict the survival outcomes (yes or no) based on some key variables which are believed to have an significant impact on the passengers´ chances of survival. Below, I explained the meaning for each of the variables.

Dictionary


##Variable            ##Description

#Survived               #The target variable. 0 = No, 1 = Yes         

#Pclass                 #1 = First class, 2 = Second class, 3 = Third class

#Name                   #Name of each passenger

#Sex                    #0 = Female, 1 = Male

#Age                    #Age of each passenger

#SipSp                  #The number of siblings and spouses

#Parch                  #The number of parents and children 

#Fare                   #The amount of money paid for the ticket from each passenger

#Ticket                 #The number of ticket

#Cabin                  #The number of the cabins where the passengers stayed

#Embarked                 #The place where the passengers embarked

Survived column is my target binary variable which indicates if the passengers survived or not. The ticket class is represented by Pclass. Whether the passengers stayed in first, second or third class likely have a significant impact on the rescue policies implemented after the accident.

I also believe that females were prioritized in the rescue efforts, so there is a lot to explore on the Sex variable as well.

The variables SibSp and Parch provide information about the family relationships of passengers. SibSp denotes the count of siblings (brother, sister) and spouses (husband, wife) that a passenger had aboard the Titanic. Parch denotes the count of parents and children that the passenger had aboard the Titanic.

This might be an interesting variable to study as analyzing SibSp and Parch in relation to Survived variable can reveal patterns regarding the importance of family relationships in survival outcomes during the Titanic disaster.

The Embarked variable incdicates the port of embarkation for each passenger whether they embarked in Southampton, Cherbourg or Queenstown.

Data preperation

In this section I am preparing the dataset before I start with the modelling process. First of all, I am deleting 3 variables (PassengerID, Ticket, Cabin) that I think would not be useful for analysis. Then I use the ìfelse function in order to give the values 0 and 1 for the Sex column.

Next, I split the Embarked variable ( Southampton, Cherbourg, Queenstown) into 3 new columns to denote the port of embarkation. Each indicator is set to 1 if the passenger embarked from the corresponding port and 0 otherwise.

The Pclass variable (1, 2, 3) is similarly transformed into three binary indicators (FirstClass, SecondClass, ThirdClass) representing the ticket class. Each indicator is set to 1 if the passenger belongs to the respective ticket class and 0 otherwise.

Finally, I delete all the rows with NA values to ensure that my dataset is clean and ready for modelling.


my_data[, c("PassengerId","Ticket", "Cabin") := NULL]


my_data$Sex <- ifelse(my_data$Sex == "male", 1, 0)
  
  
my_data$Southhampton <- ifelse(my_data$Embarked == "S", 1, 0)
my_data$Cherbourg <- ifelse(my_data$Embarked == "C", 1, 0)
my_data$Queenstown <- ifelse(my_data$Embarked == "Q", 1, 0)
  
my_data$FirstClass <- ifelse(my_data$Pclass == "1", 1, 0)
my_data$SecondClass <- ifelse(my_data$Pclass == "2", 1, 0)
my_data$ThirdClass <- ifelse(my_data$Pclass == "3", 1, 0) 

my_data <- na.omit(my_data)


training_sample <- my_data[,sample(.N, floor(.N*.80))]
dt_training <- my_data[training_sample]
dt_test <- my_data[-training_sample]

Logistic regression

In this section I run a logistic regression by using the R base function glm for my training set. Survived is my target variable.

Then, I checked the β vectors by looking at the coefficients to get a feeling of the impact that each variable has on the target variable. First class and Sex are some of the most influential variables. First class has a positive relationship with the target variable while Sex has a negative relationship.

After the logistic regression calculates the probabilities for each observation, I apply a decision rule by putting a condition where all the class probabilities greater than 0.5 would receive a 1 binary value. Otherwise, a 0 will be assigned. The accuracy of the model is 81.6 %

In order to increase the accuracy of the model more, I loop through all the thresholds from 0.01 to 0.99, calculate the accuracy for each threshold and then store the accuracy in a data frame. Then, I create a bar to visualize the accuracy for each threshold and show the threshold with the highest accuracy

Lastly, I run another logistic regression with the new threshold. The accuracy is now 82.3 %

#Increasing the accuracy of logistic regression
thresholds <- seq(0.01, 0.99, by = 0.01)


threshold_results <- data.frame(Threshold = thresholds, Accuracy = numeric(length(thresholds)))

#Loop 
for (i in seq_along(thresholds)) {
  predictions <- ifelse(model_logit$fitted.values > thresholds[i], 1, 0)
  accuracy <- mean(predictions == dt_training$Survived)
  threshold_results$Accuracy[i] <- accuracy
}

#Storing the threshold that maximizes accuracy
optimal_threshold <- threshold_results$Threshold[which.max(threshold_results$Accuracy)]


#Thresholds vs accuracy plot
ggplot(threshold_results, aes(x = Threshold, y = Accuracy)) +
  geom_line(color = "cyan3") +
  labs(x = "Threshold", y = "Accuracy", title = "Threshold vs Accuracy") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = optimal_threshold, color = "coral") +
  xlim(0, 1)+
  theme_minimal()

Tree model

Here I build a tree model. I start with a simple decision tree by using the rpart function. The accuracy of this tree regression is 83.3 %

The tree shows that Sex is a decisive variable in determining whether the passengers survive or not. Moreover, Age, Passenger fare and Pclass also play crucial roles.

Then, in order to optimize the decision tree, I conduct an exploration of hyperparameters through a grid search. I visualize the different combinations of hyperparameters in a 3D plot and also show the accuracy for each of them. Then I run another decision tree, this time using the combination of hyperparameters that yielded the highest accuracy. The accuracy for the second tree is 87.3 %


model_tree <- rpart(data = dt_training, formula = Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, method = "class")

prp(model_tree)


mean(predict(model_tree, dt_training, type = "class")==dt_training$Survived)
[1] 0.8441331
# Create an empty data frame to store the results
results <- data.frame()

# Select the optimal parameter combination with the highest accuracy and store them
opt_params <- results[which.max(results$accuracy),]

min_obs <- seq(from = 5, to = 50, by = 5)
max_depth <- c(1, 5, 10, 15)
cp_val <- c(0.001, 0.01, 0.05, 0.1)

# Iterate over the combinations of min_obs, max_depth, and cp_val
for (i in 1:length(min_obs)) {
  for (j in 1:length(max_depth)) {
    for (k in 1:length(cp_val)) {
      # Build a decision tree model with the specified parameters
      model <- rpart(data = dt_training, formula = Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, 
                     method = "class",
                     cp = cp_val[k],
                     maxdepth = max_depth[j],
                     minbucket = min_obs[i])
      
      # Calculate the accuracy of the model predictions
      acc <- mean(predict(model, dt_training, type = "class") == dt_training$Survived)
      
      # Append the accuracy and parameter values to the results data frame
      results <- rbind(results, c(acc, min_obs[i], max_depth[j], cp_val[k]))
    }
  }
}

# Set column names for the results data frame
colnames(results) <- c("accuracy", "min_obs", "max_depth", "cp")

# Create a 3D scatter plot using scatter3D
plot3D::scatter3D(x = results$min_obs, y = results$max_depth, z = results$cp,
                  theta = 30, phi = 10,
                  xlab = "Min Obs", ylab = "Max Depth", zlab = "CP",
                  ticktype = "detailed",
                  pch = 19,
                  cex.axis = 0.75, cex.lab = 0.75, expand = 0.75,
                  colvar = results$accuracy, col = viridis(100))


opt_params <- results[which.max(results$accuracy),]

model_tree_2 <- rpart(data=dt_training, formula = Survived ~ Pclass + Sex + Age + SibSp + Parch + Fare + Embarked, 
                      method = "class",
                      cp = opt_params$cp, 
                      maxdepth = opt_params$max_depth,

Neural Network

In this section I will build a neural network. Firstly, I set up the inputs and output as matrices. As the inputs are on different scales, I will include a normalization layer which takes the inputs and normalizes them. Then I retrieve the mean and standard deviation of the features using adapt() and store them with the layer. Then, I print each mean value which is calculated for X.

Next, I create the architecture of the neural network in keras. First, I add a pre-processing layer and then add 3 hidden layers with 16 units each and ReLu activation (to capture the non-linear relationships in order to allow the network to learn from complex data patterns). After that, I print out the summary of the model to show the structure of each layer and the number of parameters.

After configuring the layers and neurons, I set up the parameters for the algorithm using compile(). I indicate the loss function MSE, indicate ADAM as the optimizer and indicate Accuracy as the model evaluation metric which is very useful for the goal of my classification coursework.

Finally, I fit the model via fit, indicate once again the input data matrix and the target variable. Then, I specify the number of epochs for training, which in this case, the model will go through the entire dataset 500 times. In the end, I evaluate the model on the data and the accuracy is 89.3 %

set.seed(12345)   # Set a seed for reproducibility

# Data setup
X <- as.matrix(dt_training[, c("FirstClass", "SecondClass", "ThirdClass", "Sex", "Age", "SibSp", "Parch", "Fare", "Southhampton", "Cherbourg", "Queenstown")])
y <- dt_training$Survived



normalize <- layer_normalization()   # Create a normalization layer
normalize %>% adapt(X)   # Adapt the normalization layer to the data

print(normalize$mean)   # Print the mean values used for normalization
tf.Tensor(
[[ 0.26795098  0.2364273   0.49562177  0.62697023 29.544937    0.5148862
   0.45183888 34.98491     0.77933466  0.18038532  0.03677759]], shape=(1, 11), dtype=float32)
model_neural <- keras_model_sequential()   # Create a sequential model

model_neural %>%
  
  # L1: Pre-processing
  normalize() %>%   

  layer_dense(name = "HiddenLayer_1", units = 16, activation = 'relu') %>%   # Add a hidden layer with 16 units and ReLU activation
  layer_dense(name = "HiddenLayer_2", units = 16, activation = 'relu') %>%   # Add a second hidden layer with 16 units and ReLU activation
  layer_dense(name = "HiddenLayer_3", units = 16, activation = 'relu') %>%   # Add a third hidden layer with 16 units and ReLU activation

   layer_dense(name = "OutputLayer", units = 1)   # Add an output layer with 1 unit

summary(model_neural)   # Print the summary of the model

PCA - Principle Components Analysis

Now I will use PCA to reduce the number of inputs (dimensions) in my models with minimal information loss. Basically, PCA looks for a new coordinate system whose basis vectors are aligned with the directions of the highest variance in the data. I could then drop the new basis vectors in the order of the variance they capture. Each PC coordinate is a linear combination of the original variables.

I start with standardizing the variables first to put them on equal footing. Then, to conduct PCA I will use a library which decomposes the covariance matrix and supplies other fundamental outputs (prcomp). The model output allows to investigate my 9 principle components. I apply summary() function in order to find the share that each PC contributes to explaining the variance of the data in descending order of the eigenvalues. After that, I use fviz functionality of factoextra to produce a scree plot of the information that summary function provided. By looking at the plot, I notice that my 4 first PCA can explain 66.1 % of the data.

I use model_pca$rotation,2 to find the eigenvectors so I can then investigate how my original variables contribute to the PCs. They essentially contribute the coefficients to the linear combination of the variables that produce the PCs. All of the eigenvectors shown in the matrix V take each data point(passenger) to the PC coordinate system by multiplying the variables of one passenger with the matrix V.

I use again fviz to create a score plot. It plots the passengers in only the first two dimensions (PC1 and PC2) which capture 43 % of the variance. Finally, I can investigate how all of my variables load onto the principle components in a loadings plot. There are a lot of details involved with loadings plots as different libraries consider different things a “loading”. Typically, the direction of an arrow shows which PCs a variable contributes to and the angles between arrows indicate the difference in these directions. E.g. SecondClass has essentially the opposite contribution to PC1 and PC2 as Cherbourg. At the same time, the variables that contribute in the same PC1 direction contribute in different PC2 directions: Fare contributes in one direction of PC2 while Parch and SibSp contribute in the other direction of PC2. On that plot, some variables go strongly in the same direction while some others stay near each other.

Because of not much is gained in terms of dimensionality reduction if I keep all 9 PC coordinates, I will keep the first 4 PCs. As I said above, they capture almost 66 % of the variance of my data so it is enough to capture enough information.

In the end, I add PCA to my data in order to run the models later.
